{"headline": "Gardening Advice for Aging Bodies and Minds", "body": "\nThis week\u2019s Ask an Expert features  \n, who will answer questions on how to use outdoor spaces and gardens to improve health and well-being, and what to do when the physical challenges of aging or mental challenges such as dementia and Alzheimer\u2019s come into play.         \n\nMs. Cassidy is a registered horticultural therapist, a master gardener certified through Oregon State University, and a former counselor with a master\u2019s degree from Lewis and Clark College in Portland, Ore. She currently oversees therapeutic gardening programs for seniors at Providence ElderPlace, a nonprofit health care agency in Portland.         \n\nShe has been a member of the board of the American Horticultural Therapy Association since 2010 and is president of Friends of the Portland Memory Garden, which serves those with memory disorders, their families and caregivers.         \n\nMs. Cassidy is the author of  \n(2011, Anness).         \n\nShe is prepared to answer questions about how to simplify spaces and plant materials so that a yard can be satisfying and productive, but also low-maintenance. For example, beds may need to be raised or vertical gardens introduced as people age.         \n\nShe can also help guide caregivers in making the outdoors safe and accessible for those with dementia and Alzheimer\u2019s.         \n\nHere are a few examples of questions Ms. Cassidy can address:         \n\n1. How can I reduce the amount of weeding in my garden beds as I get older?         \n\n2. What are some adaptations I can make in my gardening habits to accommodate my arthritis?         \n\n3. What plant materials would you recommend for easy maintenance but high visual value?         \n\n \n Answers will be posted on  \n on Wednesday, June 19.         \n\n \n         \n\n \n        ", "url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/12/booming/gardening-advice-for-aging-bodies-and-minds.html", "date": "2013-06-12", "description": "Patty Cassidy, a horticultural therapist, will answer readers\u2019 questions about gardening in your later years."}